# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-forensics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] There are multiple ways to acquire packets for deep packet inspection.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Using port mirroring (sometimes called Span Port) is a very common way, as well as physically inserting a network tap which duplicates and sends the data stream to an analyzer tool for inspection.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection (and filtering) enables advanced network management, user service, and security functions as well as Internet data mining, eavesdropping, and censorship.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Although DPI has been used for Internet management for many years, some advocates of net neutrality fear that the technique may be used anticompetitively or to reduce the openness of the Internet.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI is used in a wide range of applications, at the “enterprise level” (according to corporations and larger institutions), telecommunications service providers, and governments.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI technology has a long and technologically advanced history, starting in the 1990s, before the technology entered what is seen today as common, mainstream deployments.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Essential DPI functionality includes analysis of packet headers and protocol fields.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] For example, Wireshark offers essential DPI functionality through its numerous dissectors that display field names and content and, in some cases, offer interpretation of field values.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Some security solutions that offer DPI combine the functionality of an intrusion detection system (IDS) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS) with a traditional stateful firewall.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] This combination makes it possible to detect certain attacks that neither the IDS/IPS nor the stateful firewall can catch on their own.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Stateful firewalls, while able to see the beginning and end of a packet flow, cannot catch events on their own that would be out of bounds for a particular application.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] While IDSs are able to detect intrusions, they have very little capability in blocking such an attack.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPIs are used to prevent attacks from viruses and worms at wire speeds.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] More specifically, DPI can be effective against buffer overflow attacks, denial-of-service attacks (DoS), sophisticated intrusions, and a small percentage of worms that fit within a single packet.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI-enabled devices have the ability to look at Layer 2 and beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In some cases, DPI can be invoked to look through Layer 2-7 of the OSI model.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] This includes headers and data protocol structures as well as the payload of the message.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI functionality is invoked when a device looks or takes other action based on information beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI can identify and classify traffic based on a signature database that includes information extracted from the data part of a packet, allowing finer control than classification based only on header information.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] End points can utilize encryption and obfuscation techniques to evade DPI actions in many cases.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] A classified packet may be redirected, marked/tagged (see quality of service), blocked, rate limited, and of course, reported to a reporting agent in the network.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In this way, HTTP errors of different classifications may be identified and forwarded for analysis.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Many DPI devices can identify packet flows (rather than packet-by-packet analysis), allowing control actions based on accumulated flow information.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Initially security at the enterprise level was just a perimeter discipline, with a dominant philosophy of keeping unauthorized users out, and shielding authorized users from the outside world.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The most frequently used tool for accomplishing this has been a stateful firewall.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] It can permit fine-grained control of access from the outside world to pre-defined destinations on the internal network, as well as permitting access back to other hosts only if a request to the outside world has been made previously.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Vulnerabilities exist at network layers, however, that are not visible to a stateful firewall.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Firewalls also do not distinguish between permitted and forbidden uses of legitimately-accessed applications.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI enables IT administrators and security officials to set policies and enforce them at all layers, including the application and user layer to help combat those threats.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is able to detect a few kinds of buffer overflow attacks.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI may be used by enterprise for Data Leak Prevention (DLP).
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] When an e-mail user tries to send a protected file, the user may be given information on how to get the proper clearance to send the file.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI to secure their internal networks, Internet service providers (ISPs) also apply it on the public networks provided to customers.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Common uses of DPI by ISPs are lawful intercept, policy definition and enforcement, targeted advertising, quality of service, offering tiered services, and copyright enforcement.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers are required by almost all governments worldwide to enable lawful intercept capabilities.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Decades ago in a legacy telephone environment, this was met by creating a traffic access point (TAP) using an intercepting proxy server that connects to the government's surveillance equipment.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The acquisition component of this functionality may be provided in many ways, including DPI, DPI-enabled products that are "LI or CALEA-compliant" can be used – when directed by a court order – to access a user's datastream.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In some countries the ISPs are required to perform filtering, depending on the country's laws.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows service providers to "readily know the packets of information you are receiving online—from e-mail, to websites, to sharing of music, video and software downloads".
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Because ISPs route the traffic of all of their customers, they are able to monitor web-browsing habits in a very detailed way allowing them to gain information about their customers' interests, which can be used by companies specializing in targeted advertising.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] At least 100,000 United States customers are tracked this way, and as many as 10% of U.S. customers have been tracked in this way.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Technology providers include NebuAd, Front Porch, and Phorm.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs monitoring their customers include Knology and Wide Open West.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In addition, the United Kingdom ISP British Telecom has admitted testing solutions from Phorm without their customers' knowledge or consent.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Applications such as peer-to-peer (P2P) traffic present increasing problems for broadband service providers.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Typically, P2P traffic is used by applications that do file sharing.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] These may be any kind of files (i.e. documents, music, videos, or applications).
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Due to the frequently large size of media files being transferred, P2P drives increasing traffic loads, requiring additional network capacity.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers say a minority of users generate large quantities of P2P traffic and degrade performance for the majority of broadband subscribers using applications such as e-mail or Web browsing which use less bandwidth.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Poor network performance increases customer dissatisfaction and leads to a decline in service revenues.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows the operators to oversell their available bandwidth while ensuring equitable bandwidth distribution to all users by preventing network congestion.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Additionally, a higher priority can be allocated to a VoIP or video conferencing call which requires low latency versus web browsing which does not.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] This is the approach that service providers use to dynamically allocate bandwidth according to traffic that is passing through their networks.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Mobile and broadband service providers use DPI as a means to implement tiered service plans, to differentiate "walled garden" services from "value added", "all-you-can-eat" and "one-size-fits-all" data services.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs are sometimes requested by copyright owners or required by courts or official policy to help enforce copyrights.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, one of Denmark's largest ISPs, Tele2, was given a court injunction and told it must block its customers from accessing The Pirate Bay, a launching point for BitTorrent.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Instead of prosecuting file sharers one at a time, the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) and the big four record labels EMI, Sony BMG, Universal Music, and Warner Music have sued ISPs such as Eircom for not doing enough about protecting their copyrights.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), which aims to enforce movie copyrights, has taken the position with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) that network neutrality could hurt anti-piracy techniques such as deep packet inspection and other forms of filtering.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI for the security of their own networks, governments in North America, Europe, and Asia use DPI for various purposes such as surveillance and censorship.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Chinese government uses deep packet inspection to monitor and censor network traffic and content that it claims is harmful to Chinese citizens or state interests.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] This material includes pornography, information on religion, and political dissent.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Chinese network ISPs use DPI to see if there is any sensitive keyword going through their network.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] China previously blocked all VoIP traffic in and out of their country but many available VoIP applications now function in China.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Voice traffic in Skype is unaffected, although text messages are subject to filtering, and messages containing sensitive material, such as curse-words, are simply not delivered, with no notification provided to either participant in the conversation.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] China also blocks visual media sites such as YouTube.com and various photography and blogging sites.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Since 2015, Egypt reportedly started to join the list which was constantly being denied by the Egyptian National Telecom Regulatory Authority (NTRA) officials.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] However, it came to news when the country decided to block the encrypted messaging app Signal as announced by the application's developer.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In April 2017, all VoIP applications including FaceTime, Facebook Messenger, Viber, WhatsApp calls and Skype have been all blocked in the country.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] As of 2022, FaceTime, Facebook Messenger are unblocked.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Indian ISP Jio, which is also the largest network operator in India has been known to employ sophisticated DPI techniques like SNI-based filtering to enforce censorship.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Indonesian government via Telkom Indonesia, supported by Cisco Meraki DPI technology, perform country-wide surveillance by the way of deep packet inspection, and map it into SSN/NIK (Nomor Induk Kependudukan) of its citizens that registered to the state-owned ISP.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of deep packet inspection including filtering porn, hate speech, and reducing tension in West Papua.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Indonesian Government planned to scale up the surveillance to next level until 2030.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] According to unnamed experts cited in the article, the system "enables authorities to not only block communication but to monitor it to gather information about individuals, as well as alter it for disinformation purposes".
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The system was purchased by the Telecommunication Infrastructure Co., part of the Iranian government's telecom monopoly.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] According to the *Journal*, NSN "provided equipment to Iran last year under the internationally recognized concept of 'lawful intercept,' said Mr.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] That relates to intercepting data for the purposes of combating terrorism, child pornography, drug trafficking, and other criminal activities carried out online, a capability that most if not all telecom companies have, he said....
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] He said the company determined it was no longer part of its core business.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The NSN system followed on purchases by Iran from Secure Computing Corp. earlier in the decade.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Questions have been raised about the reporting reliability of the *Journal* report by David Isenberg, an independent Washington, D.C.–based analyst and Cato Institute Adjunct Scholar, specifically saying that Mr.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Roome is denying the quotes attributed to him and that he, Isenberg, also had similar complaints with one of the same *Journal* reporters in an earlier story.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] NSN has issued the following denial: NSN "has not provided any deep packet inspection, web censorship or Internet filtering capability to Iran".
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] A concurrent article in *The New York Times* stated the NSN sale had been covered in a "spate of news reports in April [2009], including *The Washington Times*," and reviewed censorship of the Internet and other media in the country, but did not mention DPI.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] According to Walid Al-Saqaf, the developer of the internet censorship circumventor Alkasir, Iran was using deep packet inspection in February 2012, bringing internet speeds in the entire country to a near standstill.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] This briefly eliminated access to tools such as Tor and Alkasir.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The incumbent Malaysian government, headed by Barisan Nasional, was said to be using DPI against a political opponent during the run-up to the 13th general elections held on 5 May 2013.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of DPI, in this instance, was to block and/or hinder access to selected websites, e.g.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Facebook accounts, blogs and news portals.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) states that the DPI system has been installed to implement the Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act (PECA) 2016, particularly to filter and block blasphemous content and any material that is considered to be against the integrity or security of Pakistan.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Canadian firm Sandvine was contracted to provide and set up the equipment in Pakistan.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Federal Law No.139 enforces blocking websites on the Russian Internet blacklist using IP filtering, but does not force ISPs into analyzing the data part of packets.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Yet some ISPs still use different DPI solutions to implement blacklisting.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] For 2019, the governmental agency Roskomnadzor is planning a nationwide rollout of DPI after the pilot project in one of the country's regions, at an estimated cost of 20 billion roubles (US$300M).
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The city state reportedly employs deep packet inspection of Internet traffic.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] FCC adopts Internet CALEA requirements: The FCC, pursuant to its mandate from the U.S.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Congress, and in line with the policies of most countries worldwide, has required that all telecommunication providers, including Internet services, be capable of supporting the execution of a court order to provide real-time communication forensics of specified users.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, the FCC adopted new Title 47, Subpart Z, rules requiring Internet Access Providers to meet these requirements.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] DPI was one of the platforms essential to meeting this requirement and has been deployed for this purpose throughout the U.S.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The National Security Agency (NSA), with cooperation from AT&T Inc., has used deep packet inspection to make internet traffic surveillance, sorting, and forwarding more intelligent.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The DPI is used to find which packets are carrying e-mail or a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephone call.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Traffic associated with AT&T's Common Backbone was "split" between two fibers, dividing the signal so that 50 percent of the signal strength went to each output fiber.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] One of the output fibers was diverted to a secure room; the other carried communications on to AT&T's switching equipment.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The secure room contained Narus traffic analyzers and logic servers; Narus states that such devices are capable of real-time data collection (recording data for consideration) and capture at 10 gigabits per second.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Certain traffic was selected and sent over a dedicated line to a "central location" for analysis.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] According to an affidavit by expert witness J.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Narus's Semantic Traffic Analyzer software, which runs on IBM or Dell Linux servers using DPI, sorts through IP traffic at 10 Gbit/s to pick out specific messages based on a targeted e-mail address, IP address or, in the case of VoIP, telephone number.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Gonzales have asserted that they believe the president has the authority to order secret intercepts of telephone and e-mail exchanges between people inside the United States and their contacts abroad without obtaining a FISA warrant.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] The Defense Information Systems Agency has developed a sensor platform that uses deep packet inspection.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Vietnam launched its network security center and required ISPs to upgrade their hardware systems to use deep packet inspection to block Internet traffic.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is considered by many to undermine the infrastructure of the internet.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] There is a greater emphasis being placed on deep packet inspection - this comes in light after the rejection of both the SOPA and PIPA bills.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Many current DPI methods are slow and costly, especially for high bandwidth applications.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] More efficient methods of DPI are being developed.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Specialized routers are now able to perform DPI; routers armed with a dictionary of programs will help identify the purposes behind the LAN and internet traffic they are routing.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] Cisco Systems is now on their second iteration of DPI enabled routers, with their announcement of the CISCO ISR G2 router.
[src:network-forensics/deep-packet-inspection] A comprehensive comparison of various network traffic classifiers, which depend on deep packet inspection (PACE, OpenDPI, 4 different configurations of L7-filter, NDPI, Libprotoident, and Cisco NBAR), is shown in the Independent Comparison of Popular DPI Tools for Traffic Classification.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Routers and switches that support NetFlow can collect IP traffic statistics on all interfaces where NetFlow is enabled, and later export those statistics as NetFlow records toward at least one NetFlow collector—typically a server that does the actual traffic analysis.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Note that the Egress interface, IP Nexthop or BGP Nexthops are not part of the key, and may not be accurate if the route changes before the expiration of the flow, or if load-balancing is done per-packet.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This definition of flows is also used for IPv6, and a similar definition is used for MPLS and Ethernet flows.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Advanced NetFlow or IPFIX implementations like Cisco Flexible NetFlow allow user-defined flow keys.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The router will output a flow record when it determines that the flow is finished.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] It does this by flow aging: when the router sees new traffic for an existing flow it resets the aging counter.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Also, TCP session termination in a TCP flow causes the router to expire the flow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Routers can also be configured to output a flow record at a fixed interval even if the flow is still ongoing.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow records are traditionally exported using User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and collected using a NetFlow collector.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The IP address of the NetFlow collector and the destination UDP port must be configured on the sending router.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] A common value is UDP port 2055, but other values like 9555 or 9995, 9025, 9026 etc. can also be used.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] For efficiency reasons, the router traditionally does not keep track of flow records already exported, so if a NetFlow packet is dropped due to network congestion or packet corruption, all contained records are lost forever.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The UDP protocol does not inform the router of the loss so it can send the packets again.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This can be a real problem, especially with NetFlow v8 or v9 that can aggregate a lot of packets or flows into a single record.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] A single UDP packet loss can cause a huge impact on the statistics of some flows.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] That is why some modern implementations of NetFlow use the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) to export packets so as to provide some protection against packet loss, and make sure that NetFlow v9 templates are received before any related record is exported.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Note that TCP would not be suitable for NetFlow because a strict ordering of packets would cause excessive buffering and delays.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The problem with SCTP is that it requires interaction between each NetFlow collector and each router exporting NetFlow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] There may be performance limitations if a router has to deal with many NetFlow collectors, and a NetFlow collector has to deal with many routers, especially when some of them are unavailable due to failure or maintenance.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] SCTP may not be efficient if NetFlow must be exported toward several independent collectors, some of which may be test servers that can go down at any moment.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] UDP allows simple replication of NetFlow packets using Network taps or L2 or L3 Mirroring.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Simple stateless equipment can also filter or change the destination address of NetFlow UDP packets if necessary.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Since NetFlow export almost only use network backbone links, packet loss will often be negligible.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] If it happens, it will mostly be on the link between the network and the NetFlow collectors.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] A NetFlow record can contain a wide variety of information about the traffic in a given flow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] For ICMP flows, the Source Port is zero, and the Destination Port number field codes ICMP message Type and Code (port = ICMP-Type * 256 + ICMP-Code) .
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The source and destination Autonomous System (AS) number fields can report the destination AS (last AS of AS-Path) or the immediate neighbor AS (first AS of AS-Path) depending on the router configuration.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] But the AS number will be zero if the feature is not supported, the route is unknown or not announced by BGP, or the AS is the local AS.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] There is no explicit way to distinguish between these cases.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] By analyzing flow data, a picture of traffic flow and traffic volume in a network can be built.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The NetFlow record format has evolved over time, hence the inclusion of version numbers.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Cisco maintains details of the different version numbers and the layout of the packets for each version.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow is usually enabled on a per-interface basis to limit load on the router components involved in NetFlow, or to limit the amount of NetFlow records exported.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow usually captures all packets received by an ingress IP interface, but some NetFlow implementations use IP filters to decide if a packet can be observed by NetFlow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Some NetFlow implementations also allow the observation of packets on the egress IP interface, but this must be used with care: all flows from any ingress interface with NetFlow enabled to any interface with NetFlow enabled could be counted twice.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Standard NetFlow was designed to process all IP packets on an interface.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] But in some environments, e.g. on Internet backbones, that was too costly, due to the extra processing required for each packet, and large number of simultaneous flows.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] So Cisco introduced sampled NetFlow on Cisco 12000, and that is now used in all high-end routers that implement NetFlow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Only one packet out of *n* is processed, where *n*, the sampling rate, is determined by the router configuration.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Some implementations have more complex methods to sample packets, like per-flow sampling on Cisco Catalysts.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The sampling rate is often the same for all interfaces, but can be adjusted per interface for some routers.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] When Sampled NetFlow is used, the NetFlow records must be adjusted for the effect of sampling - traffic volumes, in particular, are now an estimate rather than the actual measured flow volume.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow was initially implemented by Cisco, and described in an "informational" document that was not on the standards track: RFC 3954 – Cisco Systems NetFlow Services Export Version 9.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The NetFlow protocol itself has been superseded by Internet Protocol Flow Information eXport (IPFIX).
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Based on the NetFlow Version 9 implementation, IPFIX is on the IETF standards track with RFC 5101 (obsoleted by RFC 7011), RFC 5102 (obsoleted by RFC 7012), etc. which were published in 2008.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Many vendors other than Cisco provide similar network flow monitoring technology.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow may be a prevalent name in the area of flow monitoring, because of Cisco dominant market share in the networking industry.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Also flow-tools collection of software allows to process and manage NetFlow exports from Cisco and Juniper routers.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Introduced with the launch of the Cisco ASA 5580 products, NetFlow Security Event Logging utilizes NetFlow v9 fields and templates in order to efficiently deliver security telemetry in high performance environments.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow Security Event Logging scales better than syslog while offering the same level of detail and granularity in logged events.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow collection using standalone NetFlow probes is an alternative to flow collection from routers and switches.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This approach can overcome some limitations of router-based NetFlow monitoring.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The probes are transparently connected to the monitored link as a passive appliance using the TAP or SPAN port of the appliance.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Historically, NetFlow monitoring is easier to implement in a dedicated probe than in a router.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The easiest way to address the above drawbacks is to use a packet capture appliance inline in front of the router and capture all of the NetFlow output from the router.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This method allows for storage of large amount of NetFlow data (typically many years worth of data) and does not require reconfiguration of the network.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow collection from dedicated probes is well suited for observation of critical links, whereas NetFlow on routers provides a Network-wide view of the traffic that can be used for capacity planning, accounting, performance monitoring, and security.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] NetFlow was originally a Cisco packet switching technology for Cisco routers, implemented in IOS 11.x around 1996.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] It was originally a software implementation for the Cisco 7000, 7200 and 7500, where it was thought as an improvement over the then current Cisco Fast Switching.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Netflow was invented by Darren Kerr and Barry Bruin from Cisco (U.S. patent # 6,243,667 ).
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The idea was that the first packet of a flow would create a NetFlow switching record.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This record would then be used for all later packets of the same flow, until the expiration of the flow.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] Only the first packet of a flow would require an investigation of the route table to find the most specific matching route.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This is an expensive operation in software implementations, especially the old ones without Forwarding information base.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] The NetFlow switching record was actually some kind of route cache record, and old versions of IOS still refer to the NetFlow cache as **ip route-cache**.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This technology was advantageous for local networks.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This was especially true if some of the traffic had to be filtered by an ACL as only the first packet of a flow had to be evaluated by the ACL.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] As a switching technology, NetFlow was replaced around 1995 by Cisco Express Forwarding.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] This first appeared on Cisco 12000 routers, and later replaced NetFlow switching on advanced IOS for the Cisco 7200 and Cisco 7500.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] As of 2012, technologies similar to NetFlow switching are still in use in most firewalls and software-based IP routers.
[src:network-forensics/netflow] For instance the conntrack feature of the Netfilter framework used by Linux.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Network forensics generally has two uses.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] The first, relating to security, involves monitoring a network for anomalous traffic and identifying intrusions.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] An attacker might be able to erase all log files on a compromised host; network-based evidence might therefore be the only evidence available for forensic analysis.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] The second form relates to law enforcement.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] In this case analysis of captured network traffic can include tasks such as reassembling transferred files, searching for keywords and parsing human communication such as emails or chat sessions.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Two systems are commonly used to collect network data; a brute force "catch it as you can" and a more intelligent "stop look listen" method.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Network forensics is a comparatively new field of forensic science.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] The growing popularity of the Internet in homes means that computing has become network-centric and data is now available outside of disk-based digital evidence.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Network forensics can be performed as a standalone investigation or alongside a computer forensics analysis (where it is often used to reveal links between digital devices or reconstruct how a crime was committed).
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Marcus Ranum is credited with defining Network forensics as "the capture, recording, and analysis of network events in order to discover the source of security attacks or other problem incidents".
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Compared to computer forensics, where evidence is usually preserved on disk, network data is more volatile and unpredictable.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Investigators often only have material to examine if packet filters, firewalls, and intrusion detection systems were set up to anticipate breaches of security.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Apt all data on this layer allows the user to filter for different events.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] With these tools, website pages, email attachments, and other network traffic can be reconstructed only if they are transmitted or received unencrypted.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] An advantage of collecting this data is that it is directly connected to a host.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] If, for example the IP address or the MAC address of a host at a certain time is known, all data sent to or from this IP or MAC address can be filtered.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] To establish the connection between IP and MAC address, it is useful to take a closer look at auxiliary network protocols.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) tables list the MAC addresses with the corresponding IP addresses.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] To collect data on this layer, the network interface card (NIC) of a host can be put into "promiscuous mode".
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] In so doing, all traffic will be passed to the CPU, not only the traffic meant for the host.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] However, if an intruder or attacker is aware that his connection might be eavesdropped, he might use encryption to secure his connection.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] It is almost impossible nowadays to break encryption but the fact that a suspect's connection to another host is encrypted all the time might indicate that the other host is an accomplice of the suspect.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] On the network layer the Internet Protocol (IP) is responsible for directing the packets generated by TCP through the network (e.g., the Internet) by adding source and destination information which can be interpreted by routers all over the network.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Cellular digital packet networks, like GPRS, use similar protocols like IP, so the methods described for IP work with them as well.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] For the correct routing, every intermediate router must have a routing table to know where to send the packet next.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] These routing tables are one of the best sources of information if investigating a digital crime and trying to track down an attacker.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] To do this, it is necessary to follow the packets of the attacker, reverse the sending route and find the computer the packet came from (i.e., the attacker).
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Given the proliferation of TLS encryption on the internet, as of April 2021 it is estimated that half of all malware uses TLS to evade detection.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Encrypted traffic analysis inspects traffic to identify encrypted traffic coming from malware and other threats by detecting suspicious combinations of TLS characteristics, usually to uncommon networks or servers.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Another approach to encrypted traffic analysis uses a generated database of fingerprints, although these techniques have been criticized as being easily bypassed by hackers and inaccurate.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] The internet can be a rich source of digital evidence including web browsing, email, newsgroup, synchronous chat and peer-to-peer traffic.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] For example, web server logs can be used to show when (or if) a suspect accessed information related to criminal activity.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Email accounts can often contain useful evidence; but email headers are easily faked and, so, network forensics may be used to prove the exact origin of incriminating material.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Network forensics can also be used in order to find out who is using a particular computer by extracting user account information from the network traffic.
[src:network-forensics/network-forensics] Analysis of wireless network traffic is similar to that on wired networks, however there may be the added consideration of wireless security measures.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] In the field of computer network administration, **pcap** is an application programming interface (API) for capturing network traffic.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] While the name is an abbreviation of *packet capture*, that is not the API's proper name.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Unix-like systems implement pcap in the *libpcap* library; for Windows, there is a port of libpcap named *WinPcap* that is no longer supported or developed, and a port named *Npcap* for Windows 7 and later that is still supported.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Monitoring software may use libpcap, WinPcap, or Npcap to capture network packets traveling over a computer network and, in newer versions, to transmit packets on a network at the link layer, and to get a list of network interfaces for possible use with libpcap, WinPcap, or Npcap.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The pcap API is written in C, so other languages such as Java, .NET languages, and scripting languages generally use a wrapper; no such wrappers are provided by libpcap or WinPcap itself.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] C++ programs may link directly to the C API or make use of an object-oriented wrapper.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] libpcap, WinPcap, and Npcap provide the packet-capture and filtering engines of many open-source and commercial network tools, including protocol analyzers (packet sniffers), network monitors, network intrusion detection systems, traffic-generators and network-testers.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Most current Unix-like systems provide a mechanism by which a program can capture network traffic to and from the machine running the program and, in some cases, other traffic to which that machine is attached.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] However, these mechanisms are significantly different from one another; the libpcap library provides a common API to access these mechanisms, allowing programs to be written to capture network traffic without having to worry about the details of all those mechanisms.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] A capture file saved in the format that libpcap, WinPcap, and Npcap use can be read by applications that understand that format, such as tcpdump, Wireshark, CA NetMaster, or Microsoft Network Monitor 3.x.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The file format is described by Internet-Draft draft-ietf-opsawg-pcap; the current editors' version of the draft is also available.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The MIME type for the file format created and read by libpcap, WinPcap, and Npcap is application/vnd.tcpdump.pcap.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The typical file extension is .pcap, although .cap and .dmp are also in common use.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] libpcap was originally developed by the tcpdump developers in the Network Research Group at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The low-level packet capture, capture file reading, and capture file writing code of tcpdump was extracted and made into a library, with which tcpdump was linked.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] It is now developed by the same tcpdump.org group that develops tcpdump.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] While libpcap was originally developed for Unix-like operating systems, a successful port for Windows was made, called WinPcap.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] It has been unmaintained since 2013, and several competing forks have been released with new features and support for newer versions of Windows.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Programmers at the Politecnico di Torino wrote the original code.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] As of 2008, CACE Technologies, a company set up by some of the WinPcap developers, developed and maintained the product.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] CACE was acquired by Riverbed Technology on October 21, 2010.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Because WinPcap uses the older NDIS 5.x APIs, it does not work on some builds of Windows 10, which have deprecated or removed those APIs in favor of the newer NDIS 6.x APIs.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] It also forces some limitations such as being unable to capture 802.1Q VLAN tags in Ethernet headers.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The WinPcap project has ceased development and WinPcap and WinDump are no longer maintained.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The last official WinPcap release was 4.1.3 released March 8, 2013.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Npcap is the Nmap Project's packet sniffing library for Windows.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] It is based on WinPcap, but written to make use of Windows networking improvements in NDIS version 6.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Its authors rewrote the WinPcap NDIS 5 Protocol Driver as a Light-Weight Filter (LWF) driver, a change that reduces processing overhead.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Npcap maintenance releases updated the version of the included libpcap library to the latest available, allowing software authors to use the newer API features that Linux software had already supported.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Most software that used WinPcap can be easily ported to use Npcap with minimal changes.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Unlike Nmap, Npcap is proprietary software and requires a special license for use and redistribution except for some limited internal uses.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] Win10Pcap implementation is also based on the NDIS 6 driver model and works stably with Windows 10.
[src:network-forensics/pcap] The project, however, has been inactive since 2016.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis tasks may be supported by dedicated computer software programs.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Advanced traffic analysis techniques which may include various forms of social network analysis.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis method can be used to break the anonymity of anonymous networks, e.g., TORs.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] There are two methods of traffic-analysis attack, passive and active.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] In a military context, traffic analysis is a basic part of signals intelligence, and can be a source of information about the intentions and actions of the target.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] There is a close relationship between traffic analysis and cryptanalysis (commonly called codebreaking).
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Callsigns and addresses are frequently encrypted, requiring assistance in identifying them.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic volume can often be a sign of an addressee's importance, giving hints to pending objectives or movements to cryptanalysts.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic-flow security is one aspect of communications security.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] The "Communications' metadata intelligence" or "COMINT metadata" is a term in communications intelligence (COMINT) referring to the concept of producing intelligence by analyzing only the technical metadata, hence, is a great practical example for traffic analysis in intelligence.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] While traditionally information gathering in COMINT is derived from intercepting transmissions, tapping the target's communications and monitoring the content of conversations, the metadata intelligence is not based on content but on technical communicational data.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Non-content COMINT is usually used to deduce information about the user of a certain transmitter, such as locations, contacts, activity volume, routine and its exceptions.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] For example, if an emitter is known as the radio transmitter of a certain unit, and by using direction finding (DF) tools, the position of the emitter is locatable, the change of locations from one point to another can be deduced, without listening to any orders or reports.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] If one unit reports back to a command on a certain pattern, and another unit reports on the same pattern to the same command, the two units are probably related.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] That conclusion is based on the metadata of the two units' transmissions, not on the content of their transmissions.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Using all or as much of the metadata available is commonly used to build up an Electronic Order of Battle (EOB) by mapping different entities in the battlefield and their connections.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Of course, the EOB could be built by tapping all the conversations and trying to understand, which unit is where, but using the metadata with an automatic analysis tool enables a much faster and accurate EOB build-up, which, alongside tapping, builds a much better and complete picture.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Similarly to the military aspects, commercial business relationships can also be vulnerable to traffic analysis.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] While the data exchanged will generally be encrypted, the mere flow of data can be informative.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] The rise in multi-party data communications using technologies such as Dataspaces has highlighted this risk once again.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] All of this can provide valuable intelligence for stock traders, competitors, and other business associates.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis is also a concern in computer security.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] An attacker can gain important information by monitoring the frequency and timing of network packets.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] A timing attack on the SSH protocol can use timing information to deduce information about passwords since, during interactive session, SSH transmits each keystroke as a message.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] The time between keystroke messages can be studied using hidden Markov models.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Song, *et al.* claim that it can recover the password fifty times faster than a brute force attack.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Onion routing systems are used to gain anonymity.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis can be used to attack anonymous communication systems like the Tor anonymity network.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Adam Back, Ulf Möeller and Anton Stiglic present traffic analysis attacks against anonymity providing systems.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Murdoch and George Danezis from University of Cambridge presented research showing that traffic-analysis allows adversaries to infer which nodes relay the anonymous streams.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] This reduces the anonymity provided by Tor.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] They have shown that otherwise unrelated streams can be linked back to the same initiator.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Remailer systems can also be attacked via traffic analysis.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] If a message is observed going to a remailing server, and an identical-length (if now anonymized) message is seen exiting the server soon after, a traffic analyst may be able to (automatically) connect the sender with the ultimate receiver.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Variations of remailer operations exist that can make traffic analysis less effective.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Traffic analysis involves intercepting and scrutinizing cybersecurity threats to gather valuable insights about anonymous data flowing through the exit node.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] By using technique rooted in dark web crawling and specializing software, one can identify the specific characteristics of a client's network traffic within the dark web.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] It is difficult to defeat traffic analysis without both encrypting messages and masking the channel.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] When no actual messages are being sent, the channel can be *masked* by sending dummy traffic, similar to the encrypted traffic, thereby keeping bandwidth usage constant.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] "It is very hard to hide information about the size or timing of messages.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] Even for Internet access, where there is not a per-packet charge, Internet service providers (ISPs) make the statistical assumption that connections from user sites will not be busy 100% of the time.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] The user cannot simply increase the bandwidth of the link, since masking would fill that as well.
[src:network-forensics/traffic-analysis] If masking, which often can be built into end-to-end encryptors, becomes common practice, ISPs will have to change their traffic assumptions.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark is cross-platform, using the Qt widget toolkit in current releases to implement its user interface, and using pcap to capture packets; it runs on Linux, macOS, BSD, Solaris, some other Unix-like operating systems, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] There is also a terminal-based (non-GUI) version called TShark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark, and the other programs distributed with it such as TShark, are free software, released under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 or any later version.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark is very similar to tcpdump, but has a graphical front-end and integrated sorting and filtering options.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark is also widely used in cybersecurity to detect suspicious network activity, including packet sniffing and intrusion attempts.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark lets the user put network interface controllers into promiscuous mode and is commonly used in ethical hacking and network security analysis.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] (if supported by the network interface controller), so they can see all the traffic visible on that interface including unicast traffic not sent to that network interface controller's MAC address.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] However, when capturing with a packet analyzer in promiscuous mode on a port on a network switch, not all traffic through the switch is necessarily sent to the port where the capture is done, so capturing in promiscuous mode is not necessarily sufficient to see all network traffic.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Port mirroring or various network taps extend capture to any point on the network.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Simple passive taps are extremely resistant to tampering.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] On Linux, BSD, and macOS, with libpcap 1.0.0 or later, Wireshark 1.4 and later can also put wireless network interface controllers into monitor mode.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] If a remote machine captures packets and sends the captured packets to a machine running Wireshark using the TZSP protocol or the protocol used by OmniPeek, Wireshark dissects those packets, so it can analyze packets captured on a remote machine at the time that they are captured.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] In the late 1990s, Gerald Combs, a computer science graduate of the University of Missouri–Kansas City, was working for a small Internet service provider, Network Integration Services.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] The commercial protocol analysis products at the time were priced around $1500 and did not run on the company's primary platforms (Solaris and Linux), so Gerald began writing Ethereal and released the first version around 1998.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] The Ethereal trademark is owned by Network Integration Services.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] In May 2006, Combs accepted a job with CACE Technologies with Loris Degioanni.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Combs still held copyright on most of Ethereal's source code (and the rest was re-distributable under the GNU GPL), so he used the contents of the Ethereal Subversion repository as the basis for the Wireshark repository.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] However, he did not own the Ethereal trademark, so he changed the name to Wireshark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] In 2010 Riverbed Technology purchased CACE and took over as the primary sponsor of Wireshark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Ethereal development has ceased, and an Ethereal security advisory recommended switching to Wireshark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] In 2022, Sysdig took over as the primary sponsor of Wireshark, and, in 2023, established the Wireshark Foundation and put Wireshark into that foundation.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark has won several industry awards over the years, including *eWeek*, *InfoWorld*, and *PC Magazine*.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] It is also the top-rated packet sniffer in the Insecure.Org network security tools survey and was the SourceForge Project of the Month in August 2010.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Combs continues to maintain the overall code of Wireshark and to issue releases of new versions of the software.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] The product website lists more than 2000 contributing authors.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark is a data capturing program that "understands" the structure (encapsulation) of different networking protocols.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] It can parse and display the fields, along with their meanings as specified by different networking protocols.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark uses pcap to capture packets, so it can only capture packets on the types of networks that pcap supports.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] It can also read captures from other network analyzers, such as snoop, Network General's Sniffer, and Microsoft Network Monitor.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Capturing raw network traffic from an interface typically requires elevated privileges on many platforms.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark can also be used to analyze network traffic in cybersecurity research, including simulated attack traffic.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] For this reason, older versions of Wireshark and TShark were often run with superuser permissions to access network interfaces directly.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Considering the huge number of protocol dissectors that are called when traffic is captured and recognizing the possibility of a bug in a dissector, a serious security risk can be posed.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Due to the rather large number of vulnerabilities in the past (of which many have allowed remote code execution) and developers' doubts for better future development, OpenBSD removed Ethereal from its ports tree prior to OpenBSD 3.6.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Elevated privileges are not needed for all operations.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] For example, an alternative is to run tcpdump or the *dumpcap* utility that comes with Wireshark with superuser privileges to capture packets into a file, and later analyze the packets by running Wireshark with restricted privileges.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] To emulate near realtime analysis, each captured file may be merged by *mergecap* into a growing file processed by Wireshark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] On wireless networks, it is possible to use the Aircrack wireless security tools to capture IEEE 802.11 frames and read the resulting dump files with Wireshark.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] As of Wireshark 0.99.7, Wireshark and TShark run dumpcap to perform traffic capture.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Platforms that require special privileges to capture traffic need only arrange that dumpcap is run with those privileges.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Neither Wireshark nor TShark need to or should be run with special privileges.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark can color packets based on rules that match particular fields in packets, to help the user identify the types of traffic at a glance.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] A default set of rules is provided; users can change existing rules for coloring packets, add new rules, or remove rules.
[src:network-forensics/wireshark] Wireshark can also be used to capture packets from most network simulation tools such as ns and OPNET Modeler.
